MSTest v4 removed `[ExpectedException]`. Replace it with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>()` (or `Assert.ThrowsException<T>()`) inline:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Validate_NullInput_ThrowsArgumentNull()
{
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(() => Validate(null));
}

[TestMethod]
public void Process_InvalidState_ThrowsInvalidOperation()
{
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<InvalidOperationException>(() => Process());
}
```

**Key points:**

- `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>()` — matches the exact exception type (new in MSTest v3.6+/v4).
- `Assert.ThrowsException<T>()` — also works; matches exact type (despite the less-specific name).
- For async methods, use the `Async` variants (`Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<T>`).
- You can capture the returned exception to assert on its message/properties.

